# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anaerobic-respiration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] An **acetate** is a salt formed by the combination of acetic acid with a base (e.g. alkaline, earthy, metallic, nonmetallic, or radical base).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] "Acetate" also describes the conjugate base or ion (specifically, the negatively charged ion called an anion) typically found in aqueous solution and written with the chemical formula C 2H 3O− 2.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The neutral molecules formed by the combination of the acetate ion and a *positive* ion (called a cation) are also commonly called "acetates" (hence, *acetate of lead*, *acetate of aluminium*, etc.).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The simplest of these is hydrogen acetate (called acetic acid) with corresponding salts, esters, and the polyatomic anion CH 3CO− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Most of the approximately 5 million tonnes of acetic acid produced annually in industry are used in the production of acetates, which usually take the form of polymers.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] In nature, acetate is the most common building block for biosynthesis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] When part of a salt, the formula of the acetate ion is written as CH 3CO− 2, C 2H 3O− 2, or CH 3COO− .
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Chemists often represent acetate as OAc− or, less commonly, AcO−.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Thus, HOAc is the symbol for acetic acid, NaOAc for sodium acetate, and EtOAc for ethyl acetate (as Ac is common symbol for acetyl group CH3CO).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The pseudoelement symbol "Ac" is also sometimes encountered in chemical formulas as indicating the entire acetate ion (CH 3CO− 2).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] It is not to be confused with the symbol of actinium, the first element of the actinide series; context guides disambiguation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] For example, the formula for sodium acetate might be abbreviated as "NaOAc", rather than "NaC2H3O2".
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Care should also be taken to avoid confusion with peracetic acid when using the OAc abbreviation; for clarity and to avoid errors when translated, HOAc should be avoided in literature mentioning both compounds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Although its systematic name is *ethanoate* (/ɪˈθænoʊ.eɪt/), the common *acetate* remains the preferred IUPAC name.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The acetate anion, [CH3COO]−,(or [C2H3O2]−) is one of the carboxylate family.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] It is the conjugate base of acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Many acetate salts are ionic, indicated by their tendency to dissolve well in water.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Transition metals can be complexed by acetate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Examples of acetate complexes include chromium(II) acetate and many other transition metal carboxylate complexes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Commercially important acetate salts are aluminium acetate, used in dyeing, ammonium acetate, a precursor to acetamide, and potassium acetate, used as a diuretic.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] All three salts are colourless and highly soluble in water.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Acetate esters have the general formula CH3CO2R, where R is an organyl group.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The esters are the dominant forms of acetate in the marketplace.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Unlike the acetate salts, acetate esters are often liquids, lipophilic, and sometimes volatile.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] They are popular because they have inoffensive, often sweet odors, they are inexpensive, and they are usually of low toxicity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Almost half of acetic acid production is consumed in the production of vinyl acetate, precursor to polyvinyl alcohol, which is a component of many paints.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] The second largest use of acetic acid is consumed in the production of cellulose acetate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] In fact, "acetate" is jargon for cellulose acetate, which is used in the production of fibres or diverse products, e.g. the acetate discs used in audio record production.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Cellulose acetate can be found in many household products.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Many industrial solvents are acetates, including methyl acetate, ethyl acetate, isopropyl acetate, and ethylhexyl acetate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Butyl acetate is a fragrance used in food products.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] It is mainly utilized by organisms in the form of acetyl coenzyme A.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Intraperitoneal injection of sodium acetate (20 or 60 mg per kg body mass) was found to induce headache in sensitized rats, and it has been proposed that acetate resulting from oxidation of ethanol is a major factor in causing hangovers.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Increased serum acetate levels lead to accumulation of adenosine in many tissues including the brain, and administration of the adenosine receptor antagonist caffeine to rats after ethanol was found to decrease nociceptive behavior.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Acetate has known immunomodulatory properties and can affect the innate immune response to pathogenic bacteria such as the respiratory pathogen *Haemophilus influenzae*.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Pyruvate is converted into acetyl-coenzyme A (acetyl-CoA) by the enzyme pyruvate dehydrogenase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] This acetyl-CoA is then converted into acetate in *E. coli*, whilst producing ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] Acetate formation requires two enzymes: phosphate acetyltransferase and acetate kinase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] This disproportionation reaction is catalysed by methanogen archaea in their fermentative metabolism.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetate] One electron is transferred from the carbonyl function (e− donor) of the carboxylic group to the methyl group (e− acceptor) of acetic acid to respectively produce CO2 and methane gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] Reduction of CO2 to acetic acid via the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway requires an electron source (e.g., H2, CO, formate, etc.).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] When acetogens are grown autotrophically, they synthesize acetic acid only through the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway; but when they are grown heterotrophically, they can produce additional acetic acid by oxidation of the carbon source (carbohydrates, organic acids, or alcohols).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] Once produced, acetyl-CoA can be incorporated into biomass or converted to acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] In 1932, organisms were discovered that could convert hydrogen gas and carbon dioxide into acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The first acetogenic bacterium species, *Clostridium aceticum*, was discovered in 1936 by Klaas Tammo Wieringa.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] A second species, *Moorella thermoacetica*, attracted wide interest because of its ability, reported in 1942, to convert glucose into three moles of acetic acid, a process called homoacetate fermentation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The precursor to acetic acid is the thioester acetyl CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The key aspects of the acetogenic pathway are several reactions that include the reduction of carbon dioxide (CO2) to carbon monoxide (CO) and the attachment of CO to a methyl group (–CH3) and coenzyme A.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The first process is catalyzed by enzymes called carbon monoxide dehydrogenase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The coupling of the methyl group (provided by methylcobalamin), the CO, and the coenzyme A is catalyzed by acetyl-CoA synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] However, what matters for the cell is how much ATP is generated.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] The unique metabolism of acetogens has significance in biotechnological uses.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] In carbohydrate fermentations, the decarboxylation reactions end in the conversion of organic carbon into carbon dioxide.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] In the production of biofuels, the need to reduce CO2 emissions, as well as the need to be competitive, means that this inefficiency should perhaps be eliminated by using acetogens.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] Acetogenesis does not replace glycolysis with a different pathway but rather captures the CO2 from glycolysis and uses it to produce acetic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetogenesis] Although three molecules of acetic acid can be produced in this way, production of three molecules of ethanol would require an additional reducing agent such as hydrogen gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The process may be likened to how yeast ferments sugars to produce ethanol for wine, beer, or fuel, but the organisms that carry out the ABE fermentation are strictly anaerobic (obligate anaerobes).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation produces solvents in a ratio of 3 parts acetone, 6 parts butanol to 1 part ethanol.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It usually uses a strain of bacteria from class Clostridia (family Clostridiaceae).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] *Clostridium acetobutylicum* is the most well-studied and widely used.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although less effective, *Clostridium beijerinckii* and *Clostridium saccharobutylicum* bacterial strains have shown good results as well.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation pathway generally proceeds in two phases.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the initial acidogenesis phase, the cells grow exponentially and accumulate acetate and butyrate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The low pH along with other factors then trigger a metabolic shift to the solventogenesis phase, in which acetate and butyrate are used to produce the solvents.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For gas stripping, the most common gases used are the off-gases from the fermentation itself, a mixture of carbon dioxide and hydrogen gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The production of butanol by biological means was first performed by Louis Pasteur in 1861.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1905, Austrian biochemist Franz Schardinger found that acetone could similarly be produced.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In 1910 Auguste Fernbach (1860–1939) developed a bacterial fermentation process using potato starch as a feedstock in the production of butanol.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Industrial exploitation of ABE fermentation started in 1916, during World War I, with Chaim Weizmann's isolation of Clostridium acetobutylicum, as described in U.S. patent 1315585.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Weizmann process was operated by Commercial Solvents Corporation from about 1920 to 1964 with plants in the US (Terre Haute, IN, and Peoria, IL), and Liverpool, England.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The Peoria plant was the largest of the three.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It used molasses as feedstock and had 96 fermenters with a volume of 96,000 gallons each.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] After World War II, ABE fermentation became generally non-profitable, compared to the production of the same three solvents (acetone, butanol, ethanol) from petroleum.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] During the 1950s and 1960s, ABE fermentation was replaced by petroleum chemical plants.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Due to different raw material costs, ABE fermentation was viable in South Africa until the early 1980s, with the last plant closing in 1983.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd operated the last attempt to resurrect the process at scale but the plant closed in Minnesota in June 2019.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] A new ABE biorefinery has been developed in Scotland by Celtic Renewables Ltd and began production in 2023.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The key difference in the process is the use of low value spent materials or residues from other processes removing the variable costs of raw feedstock crops and materials.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The most critical aspect in biomass fermentation processes is related to its productivity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The ABE fermentation via *Clostridium beijerinckii* or *Clostridium acetobutylicum* for instance is characterized by product inhibition.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This means that there is a product concentration threshold that cannot be overcome, resulting in a product stream highly diluted in water.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, in order to have a comparable productivity and profitability with respect to the petrochemical processes, cost and energy effective solutions for the product purification sections are required to provide a significant product recovery at the desired purity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] In the second half of the 20th century, these technologies allowed an increase in the final product concentration in the broth from 15 to 30 g/L, an increase in the final productivity from 0.46 to 4.6 g/(L*h) and an increase in the yield from 15 to 42%.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] From a compound purification perspective, the main criticalities in the ABE/W product recovery are due to the water–alcohol mixture's non-ideal interactions leading to homogeneous and heterogeneous azeotropic species, as shown by the ternary equilibrium diagram.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] This causes the separation by standard distillation to be particularly impractical but, on the other hand, allows the exploitation of the liquid–liquid demixing region both for analogous and alternative separation processes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Therefore, in order to enhance the ABE fermentation yield, mainly in situ product recovery systems have been developed.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] These include gas stripping, pervaporation, liquid–liquid extraction, distillation via Dividing Wall Column, membrane distillation, membrane separation, adsorption, and reverse osmosis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Green Biologics Ltd. implemented many of these technologies at an industrial scale.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, differently from crude oil feedstocks, biomasses nature fluctuates over the year's seasons and according to the geographical location.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] ABE fermentation is attracting renewed interest with a focus on butanol as a renewable biofuel.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Sustainability is by far the topic of major concern over the last years.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The energy challenge is the key point of the environmental friendly policies adopted by all the most developed and industrialized countries worldwide.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this purpose Horizon 2020, the biggest EU Research and Innovation programme, was funded by the European Union over the 2014–2020 period.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The International Energy Agency defines renewables as the centre of the transition to a less carbon-intensive and more sustainable energy system.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biofuels are believed to represent around 30% of energy consumption in transport by 2060.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Their role is particularly important in sectors which are difficult to decarbonise, such as aviation, shipping and other long-haul transport.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] That is why several bioprocesses have seen a renewed interest in recent years, both from a research and an industrial perspective.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] For this reason, the ABE fermentation process has been reconsidered from a different perspective.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Although it was originally conceived to produce acetone, it is considered as a suitable production pathway for biobutanol that has become the product of major interest.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Biogenic butanol is a possible substitute of bioethanol or even better and it is already employed both as fuel additive and as pure fuel instead of standard gasoline because, differently from ethanol, it can be directly and efficiently used in gasoline engines.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Moreover, it has the advantage that it can be shipped and distributed through existing pipelines and filling stations.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Finally biobutanol is widely used as a direct solvent for paints, coatings, varnishes, resins, dyes, camphor, vegetable oils, fats, waxes, shellac, rubbers and alkaloids due to its higher energy density, lower volatility, and lower hygroscopicity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] It can be produced from different kinds of cellulosic biomass and can be used for further processing of advanced biofuels such as butyl levulinate as well.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] The application of n-butanol in the production of butyl acrylate has a wide scope for its expansion, which in turn would help in increasing the consumption of n-butanol globally.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetone-butanol-ethanol-fermentation] Butyl acrylate was the biggest n-butanol application in 2014 and is projected to be worth US$3.9 billion by 2020.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Fats are broken down by conversion to acyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] This conversion is one response to high energy demands such as exercise.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] The oxidative degradation of fatty acids is a two-step process, catalyzed by acyl-CoA synthetase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Fatty acids are converted to their acyl phosphate, the precursor to acyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Three types of acyl-CoA synthases are employed, depending on the chain length of the fatty acid.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] For example, the substrates for medium chain acyl-CoA synthase are 4-11 carbon fatty acids.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] The enzyme acyl-CoA thioesterase takes of the acyl-CoA to form a free fatty acid and coenzyme A.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] The second step of fatty acid degradation is beta oxidation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] After formation in the cytosol, acyl-CoA is transported into the mitochondria, the locus of beta oxidation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Transport of acyl-CoA into the mitochondria requires carnitine palmitoyltransferase 1 (CPT1), which converts acyl-CoA into acylcarnitine, which gets transported into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Once in the matrix, acylcarnitine is converted back to acyl-CoA by CPT2.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation may begin now that Acyl-CoA is in the mitochondria.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation of acyl-CoA occurs in four steps.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Enoyl-CoA hydrase catalyzes the addition of water across the newly formed double bond to make an alcohol.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase oxidizes the alcohol group to a ketone.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Thiolase cleaves between the alpha carbon and ketone to release one molecule of Acetyl-CoA and the Acyl-CoA which is now 2 carbons shorter.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] This four step process repeats until acyl-CoA has removed all carbons from the chain, leaving only Acetyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] During one cycle of beta oxidation, Acyl-CoA creates one molecule of Acetyl-CoA, FADH2, and NADH.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is then used in the citric acid cycle while FADH2 and NADH are sent to the electron transport chain.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] These intermediates all end up providing energy for the body as they are ultimately converted to ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation, as well as alpha-oxidation, also occurs in the peroxisome.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] The peroxisome handles beta oxidation of fatty acids that have more than 20 carbons in their chain because the peroxisome contains very-long-chain Acyl-CoA synthetases.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] These enzymes are better equipped to oxidize Acyl-CoA with long chains that the mitochondria cannot handle.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Beta oxidation removes 2 carbons at a time, so in the oxidation of an 18 carbon fatty acid such as Stearic Acid 8 cycles will need to occur to completely break down Acyl-CoA.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] This will produce 9 Acetyl-CoA that have 2 carbons each, 8 FADH2, and 8 NADH.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Heart muscle primarily metabolizes fat for energy and Acyl-CoA metabolism has been identified as a critical molecule in early stage heart muscle pump failure.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Cellular acyl-CoA content correlates with insulin resistance, suggesting that it can mediate lipotoxicity in non-adipose tissues.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Acyl-CoA: diacylglycerol acyltransferase (DGAT) plays an important role in energy metabolism on account of key enzyme in triglyceride biosynthesis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] The synthetic role of DGAT in adipose tissue such as the liver and the intestine, sites where endogenous levels of its activity and triglyceride synthesis are high and comparatively clear.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Also, any changes in the activity levels might cause changes in systemic insulin sensitivity and energy homeostasis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] A rare disease called multiple acyl-CoA dehydrogenase deficiency (MADD) is a fatty acid metabolism disorder.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is important because this enzyme helps make Acyl-CoA from free fatty acids, and this activates the fatty acid to be metabolized.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] This compromised fatty acid oxidation leads to many different symptoms, including severe symptoms such as cardiomyopathy and liver disease and mild symptoms such as episodic metabolic decomposition, muscle weakness and respiratory failure.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] MADD is a genetic disorder, caused by a mutation in the ETFA, ETFB, and ETFDH genes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/acyl-coa] MADD is known as an "autosomal recessive disorder" because for one to get this disorder, one must receive this recessive gene from both parents.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] In aerobic organisms, electrons are shuttled to an electron transport chain, and the final electron acceptor is oxygen.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Molecular oxygen is an excellent electron acceptor.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobes instead use less-oxidizing (in either thermodynamic or kinetics sense) substances such as nitrate (NO− 3), fumarate (C 4H 2O2− 4), sulfate (SO2− 4), or elemental sulfur (S).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] These terminal electron acceptors have smaller reduction potentials than O2.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Less energy per oxidized molecule is released.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Therefore, anaerobic respiration is less efficient than aerobic.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic cellular respiration and fermentation generate ATP in very different ways, and the terms should not be treated as synonyms.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Cellular respiration (both aerobic and anaerobic) uses highly reduced chemical compounds such as NADH and FADH2 (for example produced during glycolysis and the citric acid cycle) to establish an electrochemical gradient (often a proton gradient) across a membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] This results in an electrical potential or ion concentration difference across the membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The reduced chemical compounds are oxidized by a series of respiratory integral membrane proteins with sequentially increasing reduction potentials, with the final electron acceptor being oxygen (in aerobic respiration) or another chemical substance (in anaerobic respiration).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] A proton motive force drives protons down the gradient (across the membrane) through the proton channel of ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The resulting current drives ATP synthesis from ADP and inorganic phosphate.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Fermentation, in contrast, does not use an electrochemical gradient but instead uses only substrate-level phosphorylation to produce ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The electron acceptor NAD+ is regenerated from NADH formed in oxidative steps of the fermentation pathway by the reduction of oxidized compounds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] These oxidized compounds are often formed during the fermentation pathway itself, but may also be external.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] For example, in homofermentative lactic acid bacteria, NADH formed during the oxidation of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate is oxidized back to NAD+ by the reduction of pyruvate to lactic acid at a later stage in the pathway.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] In yeast, acetaldehyde is reduced to ethanol to regenerate NAD+.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] There are two important anaerobic microbial methane formation pathways, through carbon dioxide / bicarbonate (HCO− 3) reduction (respiration) or acetate fermentation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration is a critical component of the global nitrogen, iron, sulfur, and carbon cycles through the reduction of the oxyanions of nitrogen, sulfur, and carbon to more-reduced compounds.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The biogeochemical cycling of these compounds, which depends upon anaerobic respiration, significantly impacts the carbon cycle and global warming.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration occurs in many environments, including freshwater and marine sediments, soil, subsurface aquifers, deep subsurface environments, and biofilms.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Even environments that contain oxygen, such as soil, have micro-environments that lack oxygen due to the slow diffusion characteristics of oxygen gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] An example of the ecological importance of anaerobic respiration is the use of nitrate as a terminal electron acceptor, or dissimilatory denitrification, which is the main route by which fixed nitrogen is returned to the atmosphere as molecular nitrogen gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The denitrification process is also very important in host-microbe interactions.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Like mitochondria in oxygen-respiring microorganisms, some single-cellular anaerobic ciliates use denitrifying endosymbionts to gain energy.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Another example is methanogenesis, a form of carbon-dioxide respiration, that is used to produce methane gas by anaerobic digestion.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Biogenic methane can be a sustainable alternative to fossil fuels.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] However, uncontrolled methanogenesis in landfill sites releases large amounts of methane into the atmosphere, acting as a potent greenhouse gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Sulfate respiration produces hydrogen sulfide, which is responsible for the characteristic 'rotten egg' smell of coastal wetlands and has the capacity to precipitate heavy metal ions from solution, leading to the deposition of sulfidic metal ores.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Dissimilatory denitrification is widely used in the removal of nitrate and nitrite from municipal wastewater.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] An excess of nitrate can lead to eutrophication of waterways into which treated water is released.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Elevated nitrite levels in drinking water can lead to problems due to its toxicity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Denitrification converts both compounds into harmless nitrogen gas.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Specific types of anaerobic respiration are also critical in bioremediation, which uses microorganisms to convert toxic chemicals into less-harmful molecules to clean up contaminated beaches, aquifers, lakes, and oceans.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] For example, toxic arsenate or selenate can be reduced to less toxic compounds by various anaerobic bacteria via anaerobic respiration.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] The reduction of chlorinated chemical pollutants, such as vinyl chloride and carbon tetrachloride, also occurs through anaerobic respiration.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] Anaerobic respiration is useful in generating electricity in microbial fuel cells, which employ bacteria that respire solid electron acceptors (such as oxidized iron) to transfer electrons from reduced compounds to an electrode.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/anaerobic-respiration] This process can simultaneously degrade organic carbon waste and generate electricity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:anaerobic-respiration/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
